I don't believe that what we are &quot;discussing&quot; is outside of the perview of this thread or of this site. As a matter of fact, I believe what we discuss is very, very important, however, I agree that I must find some conclusion to the issue with you. However, I do not believe in &quot;honorable dis-engagement(didn't work the last time). There are principles involved by which I have based a good deal of my life on and have passed on to my child and will give my life to.<br><br>
The lessons from the Holecaust are that first you demonize a<br>
           people, then you seperate them, isolate them, turn them into the<br>
           scapegoat for all the ill's of your culture or society, than<br>
           dehumanize them (i.e. numbers tattoed on arms, yellow stars<br>
           sewed on clothing) to further distance them from the human race.<br>
           &quot;Names become numbers which makes for murdering easier. Once<br>
           that is accomplished, killing them off, like rats in a lab, becomes<br>
           that much easier. Read some of the works about &quot;every german an<br>
           executioner&quot; or Victor Frankl's monumental book, Man's Search<br>
           for Meaning. He survived the camps, he developed the concept of<br>
           the &quot;only two races, the decent and the indecent&quot;. &quot;<br><br>
My point exactly, and though one or more of my friends fear that mentioning them by name will bring me grief, so be it. This is what many of those of the skinheads and the Aryan Nation want for us to do with the same folks for which we speak of. And to these assholes, I say &quot;Never Again!&quot;. By my blood, it will never happen again to Jews, Vietnameses, Koreans, Blacks, Latinos or anyone else. We let it happen in WWII, and we let it happen in Cambodia and damn near let it happen in Bosnia. As a nation, our history is atrocist in this regard. As far as Victor Frankl, I like to think myself as a student of his, or at least his writings, as you will recall, I mentioned him in the story I wrote on Mr. Quan. I specifically mention that particular book.<br><br>
A very important point in our &quot;dialogue&quot; is the de-humanization of peoples. Although, you recanted much of what you had said and apologized for your comments, you had dehumanized Lien. I believe that she is gone and the harm is now irreversible. What she got from you, she takes with her. Sure is not a very good legacy of this site, nor me, as I am part of it and as much as I want to leave, as you said, this place is addictive. I want to be a part of something that builds, that heals, that grows, not tear down and destroy. <br><br>
The box is open, we will use it to good use as I do not want to forget the millions that died in the ovens. What we speak has everything to do with their deaths. Lessons learned. There are more than you wrote. And just knowing them does no good if they are not applied.<br><br>
About Hawaii, and, not forgetting the real problems we have, you are probably right, for this reason. Patti is Korean. She is in the sixth grade. She has never encountered a racial slur or incident until last weekend. There is not a day that goes by that she is not engaged in activities with kids of at least six different nationalities. I wonder if this is so in any school in Orange County? And this is not to say that this will be the case next year!<br><br>
I believe the problem is that you believe assimilation is a key ingredient for the US to be successful. You have never given any reasons why this must so. By, god, I have never heard the word used in this context more times in my life except at this site. I can understand why the hairs in the back of their heads must raise when the word &quot;assimilation&quot; is spoken as the word that comes to my mind when I read your writings is &quot;capitulation&quot;. Why should they change to YOUR way of life or YOUR way of thinking? Whether or not a people &quot;assimilate&quot; is not you or mine decision, nor should it be our worry or concern. What ever they decide, they still contribute to this country in an honorable way. This is another one of those non-issues that people love to use to detract from the real issues. You know, like the &quot;amnesty&quot; issue.<br><br>
As long as you insist on this &quot;assimilation&quot;, you always will be stuck, and that damn sign will always slap you aside you head.<br><br>
And, Doc, I have never pushed you away. Some more psycho-babble that does not apply. I could get along by easily ignoring your posts or just walking away. If I can give up smoking(sob), I sure as hell can give up on this site. By doing so, I would be giving up on you, and while that is the easy way, you, of all people know that I NEVER take the easy way.
